.ddx/beads.jsonl:130:{"acceptance":"1. Add `TestExecutionCleanupManager_DryRunReportsStaleAttemptDescendantProcesses` (or equivalent) proving a stale process whose cwd/worktree is under the current project's DDx execution root is reported with pid, command, worktree, stale reason, and `would_kill=true`, while dry-run does not call the killer.\n2. Add `TestExecutionCleanupManager_ApplyReapsOnlyStaleAttemptProcessGroups` (or equivalent, using injected scanner/killer fakes where needed) proving `--apply` terminates only stale DDx-owned attempt process groups and preserves live run-state, live worker sidecar, active registered worktree, and other-project processes.\n3. Add `TestCleanupCommand_JSONIncludesProcessFindings` and a text-output assertion proving `ddx cleanup --json` and dry-run text include process findings/counts without breaking the existing stale temp dir/run-state/scratch report fields.\n4. Add `TestWorkStartupCleanup_ReapsStaleAttemptDescendantProcessesBeforeClaim` (or equivalent) proving work startup/pre-claim cleanup runs the same conservative process pass before claiming the next bead and emits a structured cleanup observation when it reaps or preserves a process group.\n5. Add a regression case for a non-harness descendant command such as `sh`, `cargo`, or a tiny long-lived test server under a stale execution worktree; it must be detected by DDx ownership/cwd/liveness evidence, not by broad command-name matching.\n6. Unsupported platforms have a deterministic no-op/report-unavailable path covered by a build-tagged test or equivalent assertion; Linux behavior is covered by the process-census/reaper tests.\n7. Existing process-reaper tests remain green: `cd cli \u0026\u0026 go test ./internal/agent/... -run 'OrphanHarness|Executor|DockerCloneBackend_ProcessGroupCleanup' -count=1` passes.\n8. Focused cleanup tests pass: `cd cli \u0026\u0026 go test ./cmd/... ./internal/agent/... -run 'Cleanup.*Process|AttemptDescendant|WorkStartupCleanup|CleanupCommand' -count=1` passes.\n9. Package-level gate passes: `cd cli \u0026\u0026 go test ./cmd/... ./internal/agent/... -count=1` passes.\n10. `lefthook run pre-commit` passes.","created_at":"2026-06-08T11:22:34.861350262Z","description":"PROBLEM\nThe Niflheim incident on 2026-06-08 showed that DDx cleanup/recovery can still leave heavy DDx-owned execution processes behind even when file cleanup exists. Existing cleanup removes stale temp worktrees, run-state files, evidence/logs, worker dirs, and scratch dirs, but the operator recovery command does not report or reap stale attempt-descendant processes such as orphan shells, `cargo test`/benchmark processes, or long-lived test servers whose cwd or command context still points at a DDx execution worktree. Those processes can keep burning CPU or hold ports after the original `ddx try`/`ddx work` attempt is gone.\n\nROOT CAUSE WITH FILE:LINE\n- `cli/cmd/cleanup.go:69-72` constructs `agent.NewExecutionCleanupManager` and runs it in dry-run or `--apply`, but `cleanupCommandReport` at `cli/cmd/cleanup.go:11-30` has no process findings, PIDs, process-group counts, or port/process recovery fields.\n- `cli/internal/agent/execution_cleanup.go:230-527` cleans DDx temp dirs, registered worktrees, scratch roots, stale run-state files, evidence dirs, agent logs, worker dirs, and candidate refs. `ExecutionCleanupSummary` at `cli/internal/agent/execution_cleanup.go:110-138` reports file/resource counts only; it cannot tell an operator that a stale DDx-owned process tree is still alive.\n- `cli/cmd/startup_housekeeping.go:218-267` removes stale `.ddx/workers/agent-loop-*` sidecar dirs, but it does not terminate or report the underlying DDx-owned process tree when a stale sidecar corresponds to an already-orphaned attempt descendant.\n- `cli/internal/agent/orphan_harness_reaper.go:42-152` is an important closed fix for `ddx work` startup, but it only considers PID-1 children whose command basename looks like a top-level harness (`claude`, `codex`, `gemini`, `opencode`, `pi`) and whose bead lease owner PID is gone (`orphan_harness_reaper.go:82-100`, `155-168`). It does not cover the case where the harness root has already exited but a shell, cargo test/benchmark, or test server remains under the stale execution worktree/process group.\n- `cli/internal/agent/executor_unix.go:10-29` sets Setpgid/Pdeathsig for normal harness children, and closed beads `ddx-0d7d5f0e`, `ddx-3113d524`, and `ddx-418c3849` cover parent-death/startup harness reaping. This bead is not a duplicate: it adds an operator-visible cleanup/process-census path for stale DDx-owned descendant processes that no longer look like a live top-level harness.\n\nPROPOSED FIX\n- Extend the cleanup manager with a conservative process census/reaper for DDx-owned execution attempts. On Linux, use `/proc`-style facts already used by `cli/internal/workerstatus`/`orphan_harness_reaper`: pid, ppid, process group when available, command, cwd, start time, and enough ownership context to tie the process to the current project execution root or a known DDx attempt worktree. Provide a no-op/report-unavailable implementation on unsupported platforms.\n- `ddx cleanup` dry-run must report stale DDx-owned attempt processes without killing them. The report should include PID/process group, command basename or truncated command, cwd/worktree, bead/attempt when inferable, liveness reason, and whether `--apply` would terminate it.\n- `ddx cleanup --apply` may terminate only process groups that are provably stale and DDx-owned: associated run-state/cleanup liveness is expired or missing, the recorded owner PID is gone, the worktree is under the current project's execution root, and no live worker/registered active worktree still owns it. Prefer graceful terminate then bounded kill when feasible; never kill arbitrary host processes by command name alone.\n- Wire the same conservative process pass into work startup/pre-claim cleanup so queue control can recover from stale attempt descendant processes before claiming more work. Keep cleanup lock/jitter behavior intact so multiple workers do not race to kill the same process group.\n- Update cleanup reporting and JSON shape with process counts and blocked warnings. If a stale DDx-owned process is detected but cannot be killed safely, surface a warning/operator-visible observation instead of silently deleting files and leaving CPU/ports occupied.\n\nIN-SCOPE FILES\n- `cli/internal/agent/execution_cleanup.go` and adjacent new platform-specific process cleanup files/tests.\n- `cli/cmd/cleanup.go` and `cli/cmd/cleanup_test.go` for text/JSON reporting.\n- `cli/cmd/startup_housekeeping.go` and existing work-startup cleanup tests for queue-control wiring.\n- `cli/internal/workerstatus/*` or `cli/internal/agent/orphan_harness_reaper*` only for reused process-scanning helpers, not broad rewrites.\n- `docs/helix/01-frame/features/FEAT-010-task-execution.md` and `docs/helix/02-design/solution-designs/SD-025-task-execution-lifecycle.md` if the implementation changes the documented cleanup contract.\n\nOUT-OF-SCOPE\n- Do not edit Niflheim.\n- Do not duplicate `ddx-e0de6369`; that bead owns `.ddx/harness-sessions/` scratch ignore/prune behavior.\n- Do not duplicate `ddx-bbea954f`; that bead owns dirty timeout worktree edit preservation before cleanup deletion.\n- Do not replace the existing parent-death/process-group fixes from `ddx-0d7d5f0e`, `ddx-3113d524`, or `ddx-418c3849`.\n- Do not implement a general-purpose port scanner or host process manager. Port conflict recovery here comes only from safely reaping stale DDx-owned attempt process groups.\n- Do not kill processes outside the current project's DDx execution root, processes tied to live run-state/worker liveness, active registered worktrees, or non-DDx user workloads.\n\nPARENT AND DEPS\nParent: `ddx-3106674f` (multi-worker reliability and Niflheim local gates).\nDeps: none.","events":[{"actor":"ddx","body":"{\"resolved_provider\":\"codex\